January
1
Clowdy, but no rain. At home. Very quiet New Year day. Temp 40. Ida miserable and has a pain in her head.
2
Clowdy with light rains. Downtown in the P.M. to pay bills. Frank took Miriam home & home the bal. of the day.
3
Clowdy. Wrights went to Seattle. I went with Bessner to Mr. Rudene's funeral at Mt. Vernon. Large funeral. Another good pioneer gone.
4
Clowdy Temp 48. Ida miserable ever since Christmas. Went Church. Darrell called this A.M. Wrights's went to Bellingham with a new Buick. Francis drove one. Heard via wire that Donald's wife has a permature baby boy born this A.M. [margin]Great grand parents.
5
Ida down to see Dr. Shaw with Mrs. Young. At home all day. Frank in B. Weather mild. Light rains.
6
Clowdy. Went to the farm. Got potatos & parsnips. Wright in B.
7
Pleasant Fine Day for winter. Home reading. Feet & legs no better. Wright in B.
8
Clowdy. At home all day. Wrights in Seattle.
9
Clowdy Temp 40. Down town in the P.M. Paid for Cetrycue & A. American. Card from Donald. Folks getting sleep OK. Frank to Seattle for a car.
10
Rainy Day. At home A.M. went to show P.M. "Lightnin" with Abbey & Campbell. Ida in bed, bladder trouble &c. Frank in Bellingham.
11
Rain last night 1/2 in since yes. A.M. Went to church A.M.
12
Quite Pleasant. Went to C.C. Luncheon. Big argument over new Avon road. Endorsed by the Chamber. Grant & folks here. Frank in ??? Bellingham.
13
Clowdy. S.E. wind. Wrights got a new lot of furniture. Frank went to Seattle.
14
Strong S.E. wind & some rain. Went to Mr Daggetts funeral in Mt. Vernon. Frank in Seattle. Mr Johnson came to A with me. D.A.R. Meeting here tonight.
15
Clowdy. Downtown in the P.M. Called on the Judge. Frank in Seattle. Temp 44.
16
Clowdy. Temp 44. At home all day. Frank in Seattle till night. Donald arrived from Cal. Ida miserable. Chet Leamer here this A.M.
17
Temp 43. Semi Pleasant. At home A.M. Went to Avon & took Pete Miller in the P.M. Nature project progressing. Digging ditch at Summit Park. A lot of pipe on the ground there and at Whitney & O????ity. Frank & Donald in Bellingham.
18
[margin]Emma Tillinghast died. Pleasant Temp 32. Went to church. P.M. Went to Helen W. Shipp's funeral at Burlington. Very large funeral.
19
Pleasant. At home & downtown. Gas Co. ditching in the ally. Frank & Donald in Bellingham. Sent a letter to Eva Reed.
20
Pleasant, Beautiful day & quite warm. Went to Emma Tillinghast's funeral and took Mrs. Whitney and Abbey. A very large funeral. Rev. Simmons officiated.
21
Clowdy & moist. At home & down town. Francis has a Buick Coupe. Don in Bellingham. Frank in Seattle.
22
Rainy. Went to Seattle with Frank and consulted with Dr. Palmer. Home at 8 P.M.
23
Rainy or showery. Gas Company filled in the pipe ditch in the ally. Went to the farm. Oats & hay sell at $20.00 & $15.00 per ton. Frank at Bellingham.
24
Pleasant. In town in the P.M. Frank in Bellingham. Donald here at night.
25
Clowdy & windy. Went to church A.M. Donald went to Bellingham. Temp 46. Warmest Jan for many years.
26
Clowdy. No rain. Went to CC lunch. Home reading; the balance of the times. Frank in Bellingham. Don here this eve.
27
Rainly. At home A.M. Pearl & boys here last evening. Ida to see Mrs. Subeshire(sp?). Margerite also and I took her home. Frank in Bellingham, Don also.
28
Beautiful day temp 63. Warmest day I ever saw in January. Ida & I went to Wilson's. No body home. Called at Leatherwoods & at the farm for lunch & went to Burlington to see about dressses. No luck. Frank home from Seattle this Eve.
29
Fine day. At home. Downtown P.M. Temp at noon 58. Frank in Bellingham.
30
Pleasant. Took Ida to Frank Whites. Then went to the farm for lunch. In the P.M. went to La Conner and called on Bailey at the Seed store. Frank in Bellingham.
31
Pleasant home A.M. Went with Ida and Margerite Young to show "Reducing". Frank in B'm. Ida & I called on the Summers & Mr. Summer in bed. Thurs endeth the warmest January on record. Darrell brot a load of wood from Carl Johnson with Grant's truck. 3 ricks.

July
August
September
17
Grant took us to Seattle. I at Virginia Mason Hospital and Ida went to McGinniss' at night.
18
Dr. Flothow operated on me for foot and leg trouble but to no effect. I did not enjoy the experience.

October
17
Colvin, Pearl & Nels came this P.M. and Colvin bought the Ford. I hated to see it go but it is no use to me in my condition.
18
Donald & Dorothy and son Jimmy came at 12:45. all looking well.
22
Mrs. June Burn and Mother Mrs. Adrris from Bellingham here to "get" some of my diary.
23
Suffering as usual in bed all day.
27
82 today. 40 visitors today on birthday, received 44 birthday cards. All names are entered.

January
February
8
Part pleasant. Frank & Nettie went to the Country Club House to a D.A.R. meeting. Ida not well enough to go. Self miserable. John McGinnis died at 2:00 AM
26
Rainy. Frank in Seattle. Mrs. Nelson here giving us enemas. John Wilson & Peter Miller here. Rain all day Skagit high. John came in his Model T coupe.
March
11
Beautiful day. Frank got home at midnight. Grant here talking about ditching the hay barn 15 acre. I had an enema. Not so bad. Margurite Young & Hazel Worden here. Lots of frogs singing tonight.
12
Temp 40. Pleasant. Frank and Francis went to Bellingham. No new from the Lindbergh baby yet. Wash rag in the toilet. Kelly here to fish it out but did not get it. Had a bath. The Wilson boys here. Mrs. J.S. Conner died.
23
Had an enema. Cloudy. Nettie and Frank went to Seattle. Francis on vacation. home early. Colvin here. Talking Alaska trip. Suffering as usual. Gold crown preparing to sail north at 2 PM of the 24th.
24
Nine men started for Alaska at 2 AM on the boat "Gov Hartley". Good luck to them.

April
6
Cool and cloudy. From what I hear I think this is the coldest and wetest spring in other years the latest spring since I have lived in Wash. or 57 years. No plowing or spring work done and land on the flats soaked.
17
Rain, Rain and more rain. Ida still in bed and no better. I ditto. Mr Judd and E Kash called and Frank and party of gold seekers returned this eve at 9 P.M.
19
Pleasant this AM. Frank and others unloading sand from Alaska.
25
Pleasant but cool. Temp 48 at 8 AM. Frank working the "gold sand". Judge Abbey and Pearl and Dutch here in the eve.
May
3
Cloudy AM. Pleasant PM. Mr Campbell here. Radio battery down. Frank back from sand trip. Walter Stock here to charge the battery this eve.
12
Clowdy Day. Mrs. Nelson here and gave us an enema. Lots of pain but result good. Arlie Whitney here. The Lindbergh baby found dead five miles from Hopewell, the Lindbergh residence.
24
Queen Day. Temp 50. The Akron flew over Anacortes and with the help of Mrs. Doyle I saw it.
June
14
Ida's birthday & Guest day. Republican Con meets today in Chicago. Tom & Mrs. Lockhart & Mr. Bates. (The governer here this P.M.), Mr. Kroneberger, Mrs. Lowman, Mrs. Kash. Hilda, Darrell & Miriam. Mr. Campbell & Edna Whitney called. Mrs. Lowman brot some fine Calla Lillies.
23
Beautiful morning. Ida has neuritis in her left arm. Had a miserable day. Mrs. Nelson here for the enema. Ida down to see Dr Cook about her eye.
24
Cool, Temp 53. Pleasant. Miriam 18 today. Heard Frank was going into the Cannery business here in Anacortes.

October
27
83 today. Got a number of birthday cards.
November
25
Frank and Nettie went to Bellingham. Heard Lola Wallace Fowler died this morning at 1 o'clock. Mr Marly Masters here. Gloomy but no rainfall.
26
Dark day ?????? rain. Ida not so well. The Bellingham paper says the Wilsons are moving to Edison in the Halloran house.
December
31
A day of showers and sunshine. Mr. Williams called. This is the last of 1932. Gone with its pleasures and its pain its- sorrows and heart ache. May the New Year have better things in store for us all, and this one United States, Good bye 1932, Welcome 1933.
